826
00:49:36,445 --> 00:49:39,228
to design characters that take full advantage

827
00:49:39,329 --> 00:49:40,530
of the strengths of our medium.

828
00:49:43,413 --> 00:49:45,575
We then use these characters and gameplay

829
00:49:45,655 --> 00:49:47,637
to help craft our world and story,

830
00:49:48,217 --> 00:49:50,699
making sure to take the time to create a world with depth

831
00:49:50,939 --> 00:49:53,581
and plan for any possible future storylines.

832
00:49:56,424 --> 00:49:58,885
Then finally experimenting with creative ways

833
00:49:58,945 --> 00:49:59,966
to tell our story,

834
00:50:00,607 --> 00:50:02,728
the ones that fit our production constraints

835
00:50:02,888 --> 00:50:04,570
while adding to the appeal of our game

836
00:50:05,270 --> 00:50:06,691
and taking full advantage

837
00:50:06,771 --> 00:50:09,173
of the unique possibilities of our medium.

838
00:50:12,712 --> 00:50:14,694
We did all this with the help of Deere.

839
00:50:17,577 --> 00:50:20,140
Deere ensured that we started with the question of

840
00:50:21,102 --> 00:50:22,824
how to even make a good VR game.

841
00:50:23,985 --> 00:50:27,169
From there, we moved on to making sure that we're taking

842
00:50:27,389 --> 00:50:30,533
our team's strengths and our production's constraints

843
00:50:30,653 --> 00:50:31,554
into consideration.

844
00:50:33,215 --> 00:50:37,617
We experimented and explored and made sure to review with playtesting,

845
00:50:38,637 --> 00:50:41,939
which made sure our decisions were fact-based instead of subjective,

846
00:50:42,399 --> 00:50:47,181
